-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
arrange
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
This directory contains a c file for copying files to different destination folders depending on their
type(pdf, jpg, png and mp4 are handled).

Compile: Change in to the directory "arrange" and run make.

Usage:

     ./arrange [argument1] [opt-argument2]

argument1 :is  the source directory containing all the pdf/jpg/mp4 files. Destination folders are
automatically created under the same directory.

argument2 :is optional and if provided, the  destination folders will be automatically created under it.




-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
notify
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Note: I have only started experimenting with this! Need to integrate "arrange" with this.

"notify" directory contains a C file for monitoring a directory for creation/deletion/modification of files.

Compile: - Change into the directory "notify" and run the command by just typing  

   cc inotify.c -o notify and enter.

Usage:  

   ./notify [argument1]

argument1 : is the directory to monitor.




--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
final
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
This directory contains a c file for monitoring directory for changes and copying file to different 
destination folders depending on their type(pdf, jpg, png and mp4 are handled).

Compile: Change in to the directory "final" and run make.

Usage:

     ./monitor [argument1] [opt-argument2]

argument1 :is  the source directory which is monitoring and all the pdf/png/jpg/mp4 files to this is copied
to Destination folders which is automatically created under the same directory.

argument2 :is optional and if provided, the  destination folders will be automatically created under it.

